{{ingredient}}
'''Nutritional yeast''' is a versatile inactive type of [[Cookbook:Yeast|yeast]] (unlike brewer's active yeast) usually grown on sugar beets and sugar cane. It is a dry, brownish powder that is not quite coarsely ground but not fine either. When used in vegan "cheeses", it gives a good texture and somewhat cheesy-earthy taste. It can also be added to foods as a vitamin supplement as it naturally contains many trace nutrients including magnesium and copper. However, some brands of nutritional yeast are fortified with extra vitamins, including [[w:Vitamin B12|vitamin B12]].
Important things to remember are # Nutritional yeast is not the same as brewer's yeast, though Brewer's Yeast Flakes is a brand of nutritional yeast # The recommended daily value of nutritional yeast is two heaping tablespoons and no more.

{{spice}}
[[Image:Zanthoxylum piperitum Fruits et graines.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Fruits and seeds of Szechuan pepper]]
'''Szechuan Pepper''' is a peppery spice used frequently in food from Sichuan provence, [[Cookbook:Cuisine of China|China]], but also in the cuisines of [[Cookbook:Cuisine of Japan|Japan]], [[Cookbook:Cuisine of Tibet|Tibet]], and other countries in [[Cookbook:Asian Cuisine|Asia]]. It has a slightly lemony aroma, and has a reputation for creating numbness in the mouth (very useful when eating really spicy foods like [[Cookbook:Mapo Doufu|Mapo Doufu]]).

The flavour and spice are in the husks of the seed, not the seed itself. The seeds are hard like little stones, and are discarded before roasting and grinding the husks.

Szechuan pepper is one the ingredients in [[Cookbook:Five Spice Powder|Chinese five spice]].

{{Wikipedia|Szechuan pepper}}

